    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-16T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-16T13:00:00-05:00" n="101"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d101">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.00/403: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Denmark</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-16T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 16, 1918—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:36 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3309. From a [reliable] German source it is reported that political situation in
                    Germany has improved. The National Assembly seems now assured. It will be
                    composed of 60 percent Socialist representatives, the Majority Socialist
                    preponderating so that the Government will rest on a coalition of the two
                    Socialist parties or a coalition between the Majority Socialist and the Radical
                    bourgeois elements. The latter seems more probable in view of the growing
                    disunity between the two Socialistic parties. Count Bernstorff<note n="17"
                        xml:id="d101fn17">Former German Ambassador in the United States.</note> will
                    go as one of the German representatives to the Peace Conference. He told a
                    friend <pb facs="0210" n="122" xml:id="pg_122"/> recently that upon his arrival
                    he would communicate with Colonel House personally and say “I have a letter from
                    you dated shortly before I left America expressing such and such opinions about
                    me; have you changed those opinions?” If the answer is yes, Bernstorff stated
                    that he would be taken ill and leave for Berlin within 24 hours.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grant-Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
